            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Cody Sato\u2019s story begins with a loving paradox. Adopted as an infant by a third-generation Japanese American couple in Daly City, he grew up as a white child with a Japanese name, a living embodiment of blended cultures. His parents, a quiet accountant and a dedicated librarian, provided a stable, nurturing home. Yet, Cody always harbored a gentle sense of being an outsider\u2014not quite fitting in at the Japanese community center, and always explaining his surname to classmates. This feeling of being \"in-between\" would come to define his path.\n\nIn high school, Cody was more interested in people than in polynomials. He doodled in notebooks and excelled at listening, but his grades were mediocre. The conventional path of college felt foreign and unappealing. After graduating, he drifted through a series of retail and food service jobs, feeling aimless until a friend coaxed him into volunteering at a youth shelter. It was a revelation. In the faces of runaway teens and kids navigating the foster system, Cody saw echoes of his own search for belonging. This was the turning point. He enrolled in a certificate program and became a Social and Human Service Assistant.\n\nNow 33, Cody has carved out a life in San Francisco\u2019s Inner Richmond. He lives in a small, rent-controlled one-bedroom apartment filled with secondhand books and thriving houseplants. His daily routine is centered on the 5-Fulton MUNI bus, which he rides 2.7 miles to his job at a non-profit in the Haight that provides academic and emotional support for at-risk youth. The work is emotionally draining but deeply fulfilling, affirming his decision to forgo a more lucrative but less meaningful career.\n\nHis $61,500 salary requires careful budgeting, but Cody finds richness in simplicity. His social life revolves around a tight-knit circle of friends, weekly trivia nights at a dive bar on Clement Street, and long, meditative walks through Golden Gate Park. He feels a profound connection to San Francisco\u2019s ethos of acceptance. His greatest aspiration isn\u2019t wealth, but stability and impact. He dreams of one day having the resources to go back to school for a Master of Social Work, and perhaps creating a family of his own, building a new space where everyone, no matter their story, feels like they belong."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was eight. The Obon festival felt like a dream of paper lanterns and thundering taiko drums. His mother bought him a cup of takoyaki, but he felt every eye on him. An elderly woman smiled kindly at his father, remarking in Japanese how surprising it was to see a Sato with such fair hair. In that moment, surrounded by his family\u2019s culture, the gentle sense of being a guest in his own life first took root. It wasn\u2019t loneliness, but a quiet, persistent otherness that he would carry for years.\n\n2.\nHe was 22, volunteering at the youth shelter, feeling as aimless as the kids he served. A fourteen-year-old named Leo hadn't spoken for days. Cody sat nearby, not talking, just doodling a phoenix in a cheap notebook like he did in high school. After an hour, Leo finally mumbled, \u201cWhat\u2019s that?\u201d That quiet, shared moment of seeing another person without needing an explanation was a thunderclap. He felt his life finally click into focus. He wasn't an outsider here; he was a bridge.\n\n3.\nOne Tuesday, after a brutal session with a family, he felt hollowed out. On the 5-Fulton home, rain blurred the windows. As the bus entered Golden Gate Park, the city's noise fell away, replaced by the hiss of tires on wet pavement and the dark silhouettes of eucalyptus trees. Staring into the misty green, he felt San Francisco hold him. This city didn't ask for explanations. It simply made space. The profound sense of peace felt more like home than any building ever had.\n\n4.\nIt was weekly trivia at the dive bar on Clement. They were losing badly, stumped on a question about 90s film directors. Then Cody, out of nowhere, knew the obscure answer. The whole table erupted in a chaotic, disbelieving cheer, patting his back. In that loud, silly moment, surrounded by friends who knew his story and never questioned it, Cody felt a warmth spread through his chest. This was his tribe, a family forged over cheap beer and useless knowledge. This was belonging, easy and unforced.\n\n5.\nA young girl in his program, Mia, had been walled-off for months. Last week, she quietly showed him a drawing of a dog. \"I want to volunteer at the SPCA,\" she whispered, \"but I don't know how.\" It wasn't a confession of trauma, but a fragile admission of a future. For Cody, it was everything. This small, hopeful step was the entire point of his work. It solidified his resolve, turning the dream of an MSW from a vague wish into a necessary, concrete plan."
